          "body": "Psalm 43 closes with the third iteration of the refrain that first appeared at 42:5 and 42:11. Each time it appears, the formal structure is identical: two rhetorical questions addressed to the soul, followed by an imperative and a declaration. But context changes its weight. At 42:5, it is the first self-address, surprised by grief. At 42:11, it is a second, harder attempt against renewed taunting. At 43:5, it is the closing word of the entire poem — and it comes after the psalmist has just spoken of altar-worship and exceeding joy as near certainties. The sequence matters: the vision of verse 4 is what gives the command of verse 5 its authority. The soul is not commanded to hope in a vacuum; it is commanded to hope in the God who has light, truth, and a holy hill, who is Himself the gladness of rejoicing, whose character is the salvation (*yeshuah*) that restores the countenance darkened by mourning. The word *od* (yet, still, again) is the psalm's final theological assertion: praise will come *again* — implying it has been present before, has been interrupted by this trial, and will resume when God acts. The refrain is not a pious sentiment; it is a weapon the will wields against the emotions that have been telling the soul the darkness is permanent."
