        "excerpt": "For You are the God of my strength; why have You rejected me? Why do I go mourning because of the oppression of the enemy?",
        "body": "Verse 2 is the theological heart of the lament section, and it is held together by the word *for* — the psalmist grounds his petition of verse 1 in a theological claim about who God IS, and then immediately presses that claim against his present experience. The construction is stunning: *You ARE the God of my strength* — a confession in the present tense, a statement of settled identity — *therefore why have You rejected me?* The confession does not dissolve the complaint; it sharpens it. If God is truly the psalmist's stronghold (*maoz* — fortress, refuge, place of safety), then the present experience of mourning and oppression is a theological problem, not merely an emotional one.\n\nThe word *zanach* (rejected, cast off) carries enormous weight in the Hebrew canon. It appears in the corporate laments when Israel experiences exile as divine abandonment (Lamentations 3:17; Psalm 44:9, 23; Psalm 89:38). By using it here in an individual lament, the psalmist participates in the canonical pattern of Israel's exile experience. His personal displacement from the temple is a microcosm of the national experience of displacement from God's presence. This is not self-pity; it is theological solidarity with the whole people of God under the felt weight of divine hiddenness.\n\nThe mourning-walk (*qadar* — to be dark, to go about in gloom) is somatic. Grief has changed the psalmist's posture, gait, and countenance — the same darkness that shadows the sky at an eclipse (*qadar* is also used of the darkening sun) has settled over him. Walter Brueggemann's categories are useful here: this is not disorientation-to-be-escaped but disorientation-to-be-articulated before God. The psalm does not rush past the darkness to an easy light; it names the darkness precisely and addresses it to the One who is responsible for lifting it.\n\nThe reformed tradition has consistently held that the experience of divine hiddenness — what Calvin called the *Deus absconditus* — is a genuine element of the believer's life, not a failure of faith. John Owen (*Communion with God*) argues that God sometimes withdraws the sense of His presence to drive the soul into more urgent seeking. Psalm 43:2 is the canonical warrant for that pastoral reality: the psalmist is not doubting God's existence or covenant faithfulness in principle; he is pressing the felt absence against the confessed presence and demanding that God close the gap.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Maoz* — stronghold, refuge, place of safety; a military-architectural metaphor for divine protection. *Zanach* — to reject, cast away; used elsewhere of God's apparent abandonment of Israel in exile. *Qadar* — to be dark, to go about in gloom; the same root used for the darkening of the sun (Ezekiel 32:7-8)."
